'''Buster Pearson''' (4 May 1941 – 14 October 2012), born '''Stedman Pearson''' <ref>[http://company-director-check.co.uk/director/909432479 Stedman Pearson] company-director-check.co.uk. Retrieved 30 March 2012.</ref><ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1310975/ Buster Pearson] at IMDB, retrieved 27 May 2013</ref><ref>[http://www.allmusic.com/artist/buster-pearson-mn0001252052 Buster Pearson] at Allmusic, retrieved 27 May 2013</ref> in [[Jamaica]], was a musician and producer, and father and former manager of British pop group [[Five Star]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Pool |first=Hannah |title=Me and my hero |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=7 November 2008 |page=10, section G2 }}</ref> He also owned and ran a number of record labels, most notably the 1970s reggae label K&B Records and the 1980s R&B/dance label Tent Records.<ref name=latimes>{{cite news |last=Johnson |first=Connie |title=Britain's Five Star is out to Eclipse the Jackson 5 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=27 August 1985 |page=F6 }}</ref> He moved to the UK in the late 1960s<ref>{{cite book |title=Tighten up!: the history of Reggae in the UK |last=De Koningh |first=Michael |author2=Marc Griffiths |year=2004 |publisher=Sanctuary |isbn=978-1-86074-559-1 |page=152 }}</ref> and toured as a guitarist with soul and reggae artists such as [[Otis Redding]],<ref>{{cite book |title=Joel Whitburn's top pop singles 1955-2006 |last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=2008 |publisher=[[Record Research]] |isbn=978-0-89820-172-7 |page=302 }}</ref> [[Jimmy Cliff]], [[Wilson Pickett]]<ref name=latimes/> and [[Desmond Dekker]]. He was married to Delores (née Ogeare), mother of Five Star, who also helped with his music businesses.
