'''Harold David Caro'''  {{post-nominals|country=NZL|OBE}} (1 September 1887 – 10 June 1964) was the 23rd mayor of [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton, New Zealand]] and a Hamilton businessman. He was awarded the OBE in 1950. 

==Biography==
He was born in Christchurch to Mrs Lewis Cato. He was educated in Parnell, Auckland and was employed by P Hayman of Auckland. Then he was a partner in Caro Bros, Auckland from 1910 to 1923. In 1923 he founded Caros GBS or Great Bargain Stores in Hamilton. 

He was on the Hamilton Borough Council from 1931 to 1953, and was Mayor of Hamilton from 1938 to 1953, when he was defeated. He was chairman of the Waikato Hospital Board from 1948 to 1953, and chairman of the Waikato Patriotic Fund Board from 1939 to 1954. He was re-elected to the Hamilton City Council in 1959. 

Caro contested the seat of [[Hamilton (New Zealand electorate)|Hamilton]] at the [[New Zealand general election, 1935|1935 general election]] for the anti-Labour [[New Zealand Democrat Party (1934)|Democrat Party]], polling third with 20% of the vote.<ref name="1935 election">{{cite book |title=The New Zealand Official Year-Book |year=1936 |publisher=Government Printer |url=http://www3.stats.govt.nz/New_Zealand_Official_Yearbooks/1936/NZOYB_1936.html#idsect1_1_322199 |accessdate=3 August 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120501063847/http://www3.stats.govt.nz/New_Zealand_Official_Yearbooks/1936/NZOYB_1936.html#idsect1_1_322199 |archivedate=1 May 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Democrat Candidate |url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=NZH19350918.2.33.10 |accessdate=13 March 2016 |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume=LXXII |issue=22217 |date=18 September 1935 |page=10}}</ref>

He married Rubina Ballin in 1916. In 1961 he was living in Raglan. 

