'''John Johnstone''' (born 1881) was a British businessman and rider. He was the taipan of the [[Jardine, Matheson & Co.]], member of the [[Shanghai Municipal Council]] and [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong]].

He was the head of the [[Jardine, Matheson & Co.]] as well as director of numerous companies. He was member of the [[Shanghai Municipal Council]] and the [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong]].<ref name="miland">{{cite book|page=380|title=Millard's Review of the Far East|volume=13-16|publisher=Millard's|year=1921}} </ref><ref name="leave">{{cite news|title=HON. MR. J. JOHNSTONE|newspaper=The Hong Kong Telegraph|date=30 March 1921|page=1}}</ref>

He was a keen rider and bore the reputation of being the best rider East of the Suez.<ref name="miland"/> He succeeded in winning the Jockey Cup on a pony named Ben-y-Gloe belonging to [[Charles Henderson Ross|C. H. Ross]], the former taipan of Jardines when he first went to Hong Kong in 1903. In 1904, he won the Professional Cup on a pony named Runaway Girl, purchased from W. A. Cruickshank. From 1903 to 1919, he rode in 1,178 races, winning 334, securing 192 seconds and 186 thirds, being unplaced 466 times, excluding the record of minor events such as Off Days or Gymkhanas. He was also the President of the [[St. Andrew's Society of Hong Kong|St. Andrew's Society]].<ref name="leave"/>

He left Hong Kong on 31 March 1921 for home<ref name="miland"/> by the ''[[Empress of Asia]]''.<ref name="leave"/>

