[[Image:Ritz Theatre, Jacksonville FL.jpg|thumb|Ritz Theatre]] The '''Ritz Theatre''' is an African-American oriented theatre in the [[LaVilla, Jacksonville, Florida|LaVilla]] neighborhood of [[Jacksonville, Florida]]. The theater, which seats 426, is used for a variety of music, dance and theatrical productions, as well as movies. The spacious lobby is also used for private functions. Just off the lobby is the [[LaVilla Museum]] which holds {{convert|11000|sqft|m2}} of exhibits.<ref>[http://www.coj.net/Departments/Ritz+Theatre+and+La+Villa+Museum/LaVilla+Museum.htm City of Jacksonville website]</ref> LaVilla is considered "the mecca for African American culture and heritage" in Florida. <ref>[http://travel.yahoo.com/p-travelguide-2840482-ritz_theatre_lavilla_museum_jacksonville-i Yahoo Travel Guide]</ref>
== History == The Ritz Theater was designed in the [[Art Deco]] style by local architect Jefferson Powell and constructed in 1929.<ref name=downtown>[http://www.downtownjacksonville.org/detail/?loc_id=1904&page_id=12 downtownjacksonville.org - Location Detail: Ritz Theatre & LaVilla Museum] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070912131028/http://www.downtownjacksonville.org/detail/?loc_id=1904&page_id=12 |date=2007-09-12 }}</ref> LaVilla had a thriving, vibrant culture from 1921 to 1971, when it was known as the "Harlem of the South".<ref name=Frommers/> From the 1970s, the entertainment district of LaVilla went into decline and crime increased,<ref>[http://www.jaxdailyrecord.com/showstory.php?Story_id=44708 Jax Daily Record: 03/10/2006 - Mullaney: decade of growth]</ref> but Mayor Ed Austin's [[River City Renaissance]] plan included $4.2 million to renovate the theatre and museum. The groundbreaking for the project was in 1998, and the pair were reopened on September 30, 1999. The sign and northwest corner are all that remain of the original building.<ref name=Frommers>[http://www.frommers.com/destinations/jacksonville/A29920.html Frommers Destinations]</ref>
