{{Infobox website | name = SmithBucklin | logo = SmithBucklinCompanyLogo.jpg | CEO = Matt Sanderson | industry = Association Management | url = {{URL|http://www.smithbucklin.com}} | area_served = United States | location_city = [[Chicago]], Illinois, US | launch date = 1949 }}
'''SmithBucklin''', based in Chicago, is an [[association management company]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pcmaconvene.org/features/one-on-one/5-questions-for-smithbucklin-president-matt-sanderson/|title=5 Questions for SmithBucklin President Matt Sanderson – PCMA Convene|website=www.pcmaconvene.org|access-date=2016-05-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/american-capital-invests-17-million-in-worlds-largest-association-management-and-professional-services-company-54510047.html|title=American Capital Invests $17 Million In World's Largest Association Management and Professional Services Company|last=Ltd.|first=American Capital Strategies|website=www.prnewswire.com|access-date=2016-05-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chicagobusiness.com/realestate/20111229/CRED03/111229829/former-ibm-building-signs-smithbucklin|title=Former IBM Building signs SmithBucklin|website=Crain's Chicago Business|access-date=2016-05-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Ctrl+Alt+Believe|last=Duckworth|first=Holly|publisher=BalboaPress|year=2014|isbn=978-1504325233|location=|pages=78}}</ref> founded in 1949 with secondary offices in Washington, D.C.; Old Lyme, Conn.; St. Louis; and San Ramon, Calif.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.smithbucklin.com/about/|title=About SmithBucklin Association Management {{!}} SmithBucklin|website=www.smithbucklin.com|access-date=2016-05-31}}</ref>
William E. Smith started the company with nine client organizations—headlined by the Popcorn, Seed Pea and Frozen Potato Products Institutes—and just 22 employees.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ilesop.org/userfiles/file/SmithBucklin%20Company%20of%20the%20Year%20Application%202009.pdf|title=Illinois Chapter of The ESOP Association|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> On July 24, 2004, Smith died at age 90.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2004-09-01|title=Community mourns for SmithBucklin co-founder.(Headlines)(Brief Article)(Obituary)|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-122661994.html}}</ref>
During the [[Dot-com bubble]] of 1997-2001, some of SmithBucklin's client associations encountered "painful" financial cutbacks.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/maryjosephs/2014/06/11/smithbucklin-solving-the-chicken-and-egg-riddle-of-employee-ownership/#66bd0593c68f|title=SmithBucklin: Solving The Chicken-And-Egg Riddle Of Employee Ownership|last=Josephs|first=Mary|work=Forbes|access-date=2017-12-26|language=en}}</ref>
On June 29, 2005, the company became employee-owned.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.svoco.com/news/SaleofSmithBucklin.html|title=Svoboda, Collins L.L.C. Completes Sale of SmithBucklin|website=www.svoco.com|access-date=2016-05-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/maryjosephs/2014/06/11/smithbucklin-solving-the-chicken-and-egg-riddle-of-employee-ownership/#22705d3d379e|title=SmithBucklin: Solving The Chicken-And-Egg Riddle Of Employee Ownership|last=Josephs|first=Mary|website=Forbes|access-date=2016-05-31}}</ref>
In 2011, SmithBucklin contracted for 111,081 square feet at Chicago's former IBM Building, 330 N. Wabash Ave., under a 15-year lease that was set to begin in 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chicagobusiness.com/realestate/20111229/CRED03/111229829/former-ibm-building-signs-smithbucklin|title=Former IBM Building signs SmithBucklin|website=Crain's Chicago Business|access-date=2016-05-31}}</ref>
==Acquisitions== Acquisitions have fueled SmithBucklin's recent growth, including events firm Courtesy Associates (2000);<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://business.highbeam.com/410178/article-1G1-62790019/smith-bucklin-acquires-courtesy-associates|title=Smith, Bucklin Acquires Courtesy Associates.(Brief Article) {{!}} HighBeam Business: Arrive Prepared|website=business.highbeam.com|access-date=2016-05-31}}</ref> public relations firm Tech Image Ltd. (2007);<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bulldogreporter.com/smithbucklin-acquires-pr-firm-tech-image-ltd/|title=SmithBucklin Acquires PR Firm Tech Image Ltd. {{!}} Bulldog Reporter|website=www.bulldogreporter.com|access-date=2016-05-31}}</ref> medical education provider The France Foundation (2011);<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.francefoundation.com/updates?id=14|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> content provider Information Inc. (2011);<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20110906006346/en/SmithBucklin-Acquires-Information|title=SmithBucklin Acquires Information, Inc. {{!}} Business Wire|website=www.businesswire.com|access-date=2016-05-31}}</ref> stakeholder-alliance firm Inventures Inc. (2013);<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inventures.com/News-Events/Inventures-News/ID/129/SmithBucklin-Acquires-Inventures-Inc|title=SmithBucklin Acquires Inventures, Inc. > Inventures|website=www.inventures.com|access-date=2016-05-31}}</ref> ad-sales firm The Townsend Group (2015);<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.smithbucklin.com/news/smithbucklin-acquires-the-townsend-group/|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> and incentive-travel company SDI (2016).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.smithbucklin.com/news/smithbucklin-acquires-sdi/|title=SmithBucklin {{!}} SmithBucklin Acquires SDI|website=www.smithbucklin.com|access-date=2016-05-31}}</ref>
